Once upon a time, in the deep blue sea, there lived a giant kraken. The kraken had lived in the ocean for as long as anyone could remember and had never caused any trouble. However, one day a group of sailors set out to sea in a small boat. They had heard stories of a treasure hidden on a remote island and were determined to find it.

As they sailed further out to sea, the sailors came across a lighthouse on a rocky outcropping. They decided to take a break and investigate the lighthouse, but as they got closer, they could see that it was abandoned and in disrepair. Suddenly, the kraken emerged from the depths and attacked the boat.

The sailors fought bravely against the kraken, but it seemed invincible. Just when all hope seemed lost, the lighthouse keeper, who had been watching the battle from the safety of the shore, had an idea. He lit a signal fire on top of the lighthouse, which caught the kraken's attention. The kraken, mesmerized by the flames, forgot about the boat and swam towards the lighthouse.

The sailors, seeing their opportunity, sailed away as quickly as possible. The lighthouse keeper, meanwhile, used the signal fire to lure the kraken closer and closer to the rocky shore. Eventually, the kraken became trapped and the lighthouse keeper was able to subdue it.

From that day on, the sailors told tales of the lighthouse keeper who saved them from the giant kraken, and the lighthouse became known as the "Kraken Lighthouse." The sailors never did find the treasure they were looking for, but they were grateful to be alive and returned home safely.

The lighthouse keeper, however, had a different fate. He was unable to release the kraken and had to live with it and feed it until the end of his days. He was never quite the same after the experience, but he was happy to have saved the sailors.
.

A few months ago, I announced my goal of becoming one of the most influential artists of my time. I set my sights high and was determined to make it happen. In August, I traveled to San Diego to compete at a @villainarts tattoo convention with the goal of winning tattoo of the day. Unfortunately, I didn't succeed at that convention. But I didn't let that defeat discourage me, I knew that success is not always immediate.

Fast forward to the present day, I attended the biggest convention in the United States and I was determined to make it count. I worked hard, took advice from artists I admire such as @tattmattg, @shifu_nha_omkara_blossom , and @lincolnlimartist , and studied countless incredible artists who shared their work online and on Instagram, such as @bemben_tattoo , @thomasbatestattoo , @mistertroshin and @hoangminhduc_vn . I understood that in order to grow as an artist, I needed to focus on my strengths, such as composition and line variation.

One thing that set me apart from others is that my style of work is not widely accepted by the industry. But I was determined to prove that my style is valid and that it can be successful. And despite the odds, I was able to prevail, I ended up winning 5th place for tattoo of the day and 3rd place for best tattoo in the entire show. It was a huge accomplishment for me and proved that hard work, determination and focusing on your strengths can help you achieve great success, even when the odds are against you.

Now, my goal is to keep working hard and to place first in tattoo of the day at the Philadelphia tattoo convention, the biggest @villainarts show in the US and ultimately winning first place in best of show. 

(I won 2 additional awards for best tattoo sleeve and best geometric/black work. 2nd and 3rd place respectively)

Once upon a time, in a small Native American village on the coast, there stood a statue of a beautiful princess. She was carved from stone and stood tall, overlooking the ocean. The villagers believed that the statue was a representation of their beloved princess, who had lived many years ago.

The princess's name was Raven, and she was the daughter of the chief. She was known for her kind heart and adventurous spirit. She spent her days exploring the vast ocean and playing with the children of the village.

One day, a ship arrived at the village's port, and among the sailors was a young man named Jack. He was different from the others, and Raven couldn't help but feel drawn to him. They spent many days together, talking and laughing, and soon they fell deeply in love.

Jack promised Raven that he would return to her one day, and she believed him. She waited for him at the port every day, watching the ships come and go, hoping to see his face among the sailors. But as the days turned into months, and the months turned into years, Jack never returned.

Raven grew old, but her love for Jack never faded. She waited for him at the port until the day she died. The villagers, moved by her devotion, built the statue in her honor. The statue was of Raven, sitting at the port, looking out to the sea, waiting for her love to return.

The villagers would tell the story of Raven and Jack to their children, and the statue became a symbol of love and sacrifice. It stood for many years, watching over the village and protecting it from the sea. Some villagers believed that Raven's spirit still remained within the statue, waiting for Jack's return.

The statue of the princess Raven remains in the village as a monument and a testament to the love story of Raven and Jack, even though he never returned, but Raven's love was eternal
.

Once upon a time, there was a small village that was plagued by two vengeful spirits, an undead geisha and a skeleton samurai. The villagers lived in peace for most of the year, but every year, on the same night, the spirits would come and haunt the village, causing fear and anxiety among the residents.

The villagers tried everything to get rid of the spirits, but nothing seemed to work. They sought out priests and shamans, but nothing could banish the spirits from the village. It seemed as though the villagers were doomed to live in fear every year.

One day, an old wise woman from the village, told them about the power of peony flowers. She explained that the spirits were once in love in their past lives, but their love was cut short, and they were cursed to walk the earth as vengeful spirits. She told the villagers that the only way to calm the spirits down and make them leave the village was to place peony flowers at the front of their homes.

The villagers were skeptical, but they had nothing to lose, so they decided to try it. They went to the nearby fields and picked a large number of peony flowers. They placed them at the front of their homes, and to their surprise, the spirits did not enter their homes that night.

The villagers were overjoyed and they continued to leave peony flowers at the front of their homes every year on the same night. The spirits never bothered them again, and the village was finally at peace. The villagers realized that the peony flowers had the power to soothe the spirits and bring them peace, and so they planted a large peony garden at the edge of the village.

The undead geisha and the skeleton samurai would come to visit the garden every year on the same night, and they would look at the flowers in silence. The villagers knew that the spirits were finally at peace and they were no longer vengeful. They could finally sleep soundly in their homes, knowing that the spirits would never bother them again. And the peony flowers became a symbol of the village's peace and love

Hey everyone,

I wanted to talk about a topic that's really important to me: creating beautiful tattoos on more melanated skin. Unfortunately, there's still a misconception out there that tattoos won't look good on darker skin tones. I recently had a conversation with someone who told my dark-skinned brother not to get tattoos because of this belief, and it really upset me.

The truth is, tattoos can look absolutely stunning on all skin tones, including darker ones. It's all about finding an artist who understands how to work with melanated skin and bring out its unique beauty. As a tattoo artist myself, I'm committed to doing just that. I've worked with many clients who have darker skin and the results have been amazing.

Of course, there's still a long way to go in terms of breaking down biases and misconceptions about tattoos on darker skin. It's true that people on Instagram are less likely to engage with posts featuring tattoos on darker skin tones due to internalized biases. But I'm not going to let that stop me. I'll keep creating beautiful art on dark skin in the hopes of changing people's minds, one tattoo at a time.

So here's a set of tattoos I've done on dark skin to showcase just how gorgeous they can be. Let's spread the word that tattoos are for everyone, regardless of skin tone.

🇵🇭🇵🇭🇵🇭Long ago, in the Philippines, there was a powerful dragon named Bakunawa. Bakunawa was feared by many, as it would swallow the moon during eclipses and cause great chaos and destruction.

One day, a brave group of warriors set out to defeat Bakunawa and save the moon. They battled fiercely with the dragon for many days, until finally, they were able to overpower Bakunawa and cut off one of its heads.

As Bakunawa lay defeated, a mysterious force transformed the dragon's head into a beautiful mask, adorned with intricate designs and the delicate scent of sampaguita flowers. The mask was imbued with the dragon's power, and the moon itself seemed to shine through the mask's eyes.

The warriors were amazed by the transformation and decided to keep the mask as a symbol of their victory over the fearsome Bakunawa. From that day on, the mask was passed down from generation to generation as a reminder of the bravery and strength of their ancestors.

As time passed, the mask became a cherished artifact and was used in traditional Filipino ceremonies and rituals. The sampaguita flowers were often used to adorn the mask, and the moon's influence could be felt whenever it was worn.

And so, the legend of Bakunawa dragon turning into a mask lives on, with the moon and sampaguita flowers forever entwined in the story of this powerful symbol of Filipino culture and history.

The treehouse was built around an enormous, gnarled old tree that had been there for as long as anyone could remember. It was said that the tree was cursed, and that whoever climbed the spiral stairs that led to the top of the treehouse would never be seen again. But despite the stories, a group of young adventurers decided to explore the forest and see the treehouse for themselves.

As they wandered through the forest, they came across spiral stairs, leading up into the canopy of the forest. The stairs seemed to stretch on forever, twisting and turning until they seemed to lead to nowhere at all. But the adventurers pressed on, and eventually reached the top of the treehouse.

Inside, they found a room that was almost entirely empty. As they looked around, they heard a sound, like a soft whisper, coming from outside. When they looked out the window, they saw a mysterious woman standing in the clearing below.

The woman was beautiful and was tall and slender, with long, flowing hair and a dress that seemed to be made of spiderwebs. She had a strange, hypnotic quality about her, and as she moved, the adventurers felt a strange sensation, like they were being pulled towards her by invisible strings.

I will be posting part 2 tomorrow! the other side of this lower leg tells the rest of the story! 
.

Part 2!!!

As the adventurers looked down at the mysterious woman, they felt their bodies beginning to move of their own accord, as if they were being controlled like marionettes. They stumbled towards the door, unable to resist the pull of the woman's strings.

As they stepped outside, they saw that the woman was now holding a set of silver strings in her hands, which seemed to be connected to each of the adventurers' limbs. With a wave of her hand, she began to pull the strings, causing the adventurers to move in unison, like a puppeteer controlling her marionettes.

The adventurers tried to resist, but it was no use. They were completely under the woman's control, unable to move or even speak without her permission. She led them deeper into the forest, pulling them along like a strange, macabre parade.

Finally, they arrived at a clearing, where a strange, twisted tree stood at the center. The woman began to dance around the tree, pulling on the strings and causing the adventurers to dance with her. They tried to break free, but it was no use. They were completely at her mercy.
As the dance continued, the adventurers felt their minds beginning to slip away. They could feel the woman's influence over them growing stronger with every passing moment, until they were no longer themselves at all. They had become nothing more than puppets, controlled by the whims of the mysterious woman in the strange forest.

And so the adventurers remained, trapped in the forest forever, dancing to the tune of the Marionette Mistress.

Ever wonder what it truly means to fly too close to the sun? ☀️ Here's a little history for you: Meet Icarus, an ancient Greek dude with the audacious dream to touch the sky. Gifted with wings made from feathers and wax by his genius inventor dad, Daedalus, Icarus was warned not to fly too high or too low.

The story goes that despite his father's words, Icarus, full of youthful arrogance and intoxicated by the exhilarating freedom of flight, ignored the caution and soared towards the sun. The heat was too much for his fragile wings, melting the wax and leading to his tragic fall into the sea. 🌊😱

A chilling tale of ambition, isn't it? But here's the catch: Isn't it also a testament to the human spirit, the unquenchable thirst for freedom and exploration, no matter the consequences? 🌍✨

Each of these eyes represents a stage in the grieving process. 

Stage 1: Denial, when reality feels like a distant dream.

Stage 2: Anger, the fire within that fuels our desire for change.

Stage 3: Bargaining, seeking a glimmer of hope in the midst of pain.

Stage 4: Depression, a storm that tests our resilience, but we find strength in vulnerability.

Stage 5: Acceptance, the calm after the storm, where healing begins.

Each mark tells a story, a testament to growth, resilience, and the beauty of the human spirit.

Fenrir is one of the most infamous creatures in Norse legends, being a gigantic, monstrous wolf, and the son of the trickster god Loki.

In the myth, Fenrir grows at an alarming rate and the gods fear his power. To prevent him from wreaking havoc, the gods decide to chain him. They create two sets of shackles, both of which Fenrir breaks with ease. Realizing they need to be craftier to contain Fenrir, they commission the dwarves to create a magical, unbreakable chain named Gleipnir.

Gleipnir is made from six impossible things: the sound of a cat's footfall, the beard of a woman, the roots of a mountain, the sinews of a bear, the breath of a fish, and the spittle of a bird. Fenrir, suspecting trickery but not wanting to be called a coward, allows the gods to bind him with Gleipnir, as long as one of them places their hand in his mouth as a show of good faith. The god Tyr volunteers, and when Fenrir finds he cannot break free of Gleipnir, he bites off Tyr's hand.

According to the prophecy, Fenrir will remain bound until the events of Ragnarok, the end of the world in Norse mythology, at which point he will break free and consume everything in his path, including the god Odin.

In "Chainsaw Man," Aki Hayakawa's relationship with his fox devil resonates with themes of redemption, sacrifice, and the battle between light and darkness. Aki's journey, driven by revenge against the devil that took his family, parallels the biblical narrative of individuals grappling with personal demons and the temptation to stray from a righteous path. The fox devil, though a manifestation of human fear a straight up agent of evil, shows moments of restraint and loyalty toward Aki, it reminds us of the belief that even the most lost souls can find redemption in acts of genuine love and sacrifice. This dynamic partnership between Aki and the fox devil reminds us of the transformative power of grace and the inherent worth found in every individual, no matter how tarnished they may seem
